          "text": "Leo, your examples invalidate the word “artifact.” A dashboard with access to family records, Telegram, calendars, photos, or Home Assistant is executable software with delegated authority. Treating it like a fancy generated file would create an exfiltration and physical-control vulnerability.\n\nThe clean model is: one product and one policy engine, but distinct resources and isolation domains.\n\n| Resource | Meaning |\n|---|---|\n| **Home** | User-owned logical namespace. Unified UX, search, permissions, audit, and APIs—not one shared directory. |\n| **Knowledge Space** | Markdown source of truth backed by Git. User/family/team owned. |\n| **Project** | Contextual view over selected spaces, chats, connectors, apps, and artifacts. It does not own the data. |\n| **Run workspace** | Agent scratch area: downloads, drafts, intermediate files. Isolated and disposable/snapshot-backed. |\n| **Artifact** | Generated, versioned output running as a powerless sandboxed preview. No persistent credentials or background execution. |\n| **App** | An explicitly installed/promoted artifact with an identity, manifest, isolated runtime, persistent data, and granted capabilities. |\n| **Connector** | System-managed integration with Google, Telegram, Immich, Home Assistant, MCP, etc. It brokers credentials and operations. |\n\nGit-first should work like this:\n\n- One logical accepted KB changeset becomes one commit—not every filesystem write.\n- Commits record actor, agent run, sources, and approval where applicable.\n- Agents submit patches through the platform; low-risk changes may auto-commit.\n- Search indexes remain rebuildable projections.\n- Untrusted runtimes never receive the vault as a writable mount.\n- Git repositories align with access boundaries. A sealed or shared space needs a separate repository because Git history cannot safely enforce folder-level access after cloning. **Confidence: high** given your portability requirement.\n\nApps and artifacts