          "type": "assistant",
          "text": "Leo, yes to `jj` as the revision engine. No to replacing llame’s operational/control API with `jj`. Jujutsu handles revision mechanics; it cannot enforce tenancy, approvals, provenance, indexing, or policy.\n\n### Recommended model\n\n```text\nKnowledge Space      = Git-compatible repository + ACL boundary\nMutating change      = isolated jj workspace/change\nAccepted changeset   = immutable Git commit on main\nJujutsu operation log = local workflow metadata\nPostgres             = authorization, lifecycle, approvals, audit\n```\n\nUse a workspace per **mutating change session**, provisioned lazily—not per chat or read-only run. Jujutsu workspaces share repository objects while maintaining separate working-copy commits and sparse patterns, matching the parallel-agent requirement. [Official workspace reference](https://docs.jj-vcs.dev/latest/cli-reference/#jj-workspace)\n\nWith `jj`, branches are unnecessary for internal WIP:\n\n1. Create workspace/change from the current canonical revision.\n2. Agent edits only that working copy.\n3. Snapshot into one or more semantic commits.\n4. Rebase onto current `main`.\n5. If conflicts appear, keep the proposal conflicted; never advance `main`.\n6. Run knowledge validation and approval policy.\n7. A serialized landing worker advances `main`.\n8. Reindex only the landed revision.\n9. Forget and destroy the workspace after retention expires.\n\nJujutsu’s operation log handles concurrent repository operations, and conflicts can exist as first-class committed states. That improves orchestration, but conflicts still exist and require resolution. [Concurrency model](https://docs.jj-vcs.dev/latest/technical/concurrency/), [conflict model](https://docs.jj-vcs.dev/latest/conflicts/)\n\n### Abstraction options\n\n| Approach | Verdict |\n|---|---|\n| Expose unrestricted `jj` directly to agents | Reject. Couples agents to infrastructure and lets them mutate shared repository metadata. |\n| **llame change service backed by `jj`** | Recommended. Semantic policy boundary with better revision mechanics underneath. |\n| Git worktrees behind the same service | Acceptable fallback. More mature, but clumsier WIP/rewrite/conflict handling. |\n\nThe agent-facing tools should remain semantic:\n\n```text\nedit_knowledge\ninspect_knowledge_diff\nsubmit_knowledge_change\nresolve_knowledge_conflict\n```\n\nInternally these may invoke pinned, narrowly allowlisted `jj` commands. Current Jujutsu releases still change monthly—0.43.0 shipped July 1, 2026—so the adapter must pin a version rather than embed `jj` terminology throughout llame’s domain model. [Official changelog](https://docs.jj-vcs.dev/latest/changelog/)\n\n### Security correction\n\nA `jj workspace` is not a sandbox. Secondary workspaces point back to repository metadata stored with the initial workspace. Sparse patterns reduce checked-out files; they are not authorization.\n\nTherefore:\n\n- Trusted revision service owns `.jj` and `.git`.\n- Sandboxed agents see only their working tree, not shared repository metadata.\n- Shell-capable or hostile-code runs should receive an isolated clone/snapshot, with their final patch imported by the trusted service.\n- Narrow knowledge-editing agents can safely use shared `jj` workspaces when all file operations are mediated.\n\n### Git/GitHub compatibility\n\nUse a Git-backed, preferably non-colocated repository inside the service. Export/push explicitly. GitHub, Obsidian, and ordinary Git clients remain compatible without allowing background Git tools to interfere with Jujutsu state. The official documentation warns about confusing states and remaining bugs when mutating Git and `jj` commands are interleaved in colocated workspaces. [Git compatibility](https://docs.jj-vcs.dev/latest/git-compatibility/)\n\nOne non-obvious limitation: pushing to GitHub preserves Git commits and bookmarks, not Jujutsu’s operation log or abandoned WIP. Therefore portable recovery must rely on sealed Git commits plus llame’s audit records—not `jj undo`. This is an inference from Jujutsu’s separate operation-log and Git-push models. **Confidence: high.**\n\nOverall recommendation: adopt `jj` behind a narrow adapter. **Confidence: moderate-high.** The architecture is strong; the remaining risk is dependency churn, not conceptual fit.\n\nThe next decision is whether commits pushed from Obsidian or another machine become canonical immediately, or enter llame as external proposals through the same validation and landing pipeline. I recommend the latter.",
