          "type": "assistant",
          "text": "Leo, shared KBs force a correction to the current SPEC: a Project cannot “contain” knowledge, chats, artifacts, connectors, and credentials as one ownership bucket. It should compose references to independently governed resources.\n\nThe dangerous case is corporate knowledge entering personal context. Once that happens, ordinary read ACLs are insufficient—the system must govern where derived answers, summaries, memories, artifacts, embeddings, and messages may go.\n\n### Recommended model: federated Knowledge Spaces\n\n| Primitive | Responsibility |\n|---|---|\n| **Security domain** | Governance authority: personal, family/group, or organization |\n| **Knowledge Space** | One owner domain, one Git repository, one policy root |\n| **Membership** | Grants `query`, `read`, `propose`, `land`, `export`, or `manage` |\n| **Project** | Context recipe mounting Spaces, connectors, apps, and agents |\n| **Run** | Frozen capability snapshot containing readable sources and writable destination |\n| **Transfer** | Explicit movement or derivation across security domains |\n\nA Space always has one governing principal:\n\n```text\nuser:leo\ngroup:leo-family\norganization:acme\n```\n\n“Shared ownership” means ownership by a group principal, not ambiguous ownership by several individuals.\n\nA personal Space shared with Acme remains personal and revocable. If Acme must own the information permanently, it is explicitly transferred into an Acme-owned Space as a new commit with provenance.\n\n### Access and information flow\n\nRead authorization:\n\n```text\nmembership\n∩ space policy\n∩ project/run grant\n∩ agent/app capability\n∩ permitted model/provider\n```\n\nWrite authorization adds an information-flow rule:\n\n```text\ndestination must accept every source domain used by the run\n```\n\nThe security review changes one important detail: use coarse run-level lineage, not AI-based document classification.\n\nAfter a run reads corporate data, all of its derived state is corporate or mixed:\n\n- Answer and transcript\n- Compacted summaries\n- Workspace files\n- Artifacts and application state\n- Memory extractions\n- Knowledge patches\n- Tool arguments and connector payloads\n- Relevant logs and caches\n\nNo silent downgrade into personal memory or a personal vault. Mixed-domain runs should initially be read-only; sending, exporting, publishing, or writing knowledge becomes an explicit transfer proposal.\n\n### Expected behavior\n\n- Personal Spaces owned by the same user may cross-recall by default.\n- Family/team Spaces require an explicit grant, which may be remembered for that Project.\n- Corporate Spaces require both user membership and corporate policy. User consent alone cannot override corporate restrictions.\n- Corporate-derived facts never enter personal `memory_facts`.\n- A corporate Space may restrict which model providers, MCP servers, connectors, or execution nodes can see its content.\n- A tax run using personal work-income and pet-project data remains personal.\n- A personal run consulting Acme’s KB produces an Acme-governed or explicitly mixed result.\n- Wife-visible free/busy should be a narrow capability view, not access to the calendar or an entire shared KB.\n\n### Git implications\n\nOne repository corresponds to one history/export boundary. If two departments cannot inspect each other’s history, they need separate Spaces—not folder ACLs.\n\nAlso separate:\n\n```text\nquery/read permission ≠ clone/export permission\n```\n\nA Git clone contains history, including deleted material, and cannot be revoked. Most corporate viewers should query through llame rather than receive repository access.\n\nShared edits still use the agreed Jujutsu workflow:\n\n```text\nmember proposes change\n→ isolated workspace\n→ policy/reviewer validation\n→ trusted landing service\n→ accepted Space revision\n```\n\nExternal Notion, Confluence, or corporate Git sources can remain upstream-canonical. llame mounts and indexes them; writeback becomes an upstream proposal or pull request.\n\n### MVP boundary\n\nBuild only:\n\n1. User/group/organization-owned Spaces.\n2. Explicit action grants.\n3. Per-run source set, destination scope, and policy snapshot.\n4. Same-domain runs by default.\n5. Explicit read-only mixed-domain runs with most-restrictive retention.\n6. Separate clone/export permission.\n7. Revocation that terminates runs, destroys workspaces, and invalidates indexes/caches.\n\nDefer per-paragraph classification, automatic redaction, full DLP, and cross-instance federation.\n\nDo you accept making the **Run—not the Chat—the durable security boundary**, while initially limiting the UI to one active security domain at a time? I recommend that model. **Confidence: high.**",
