r persistent\\n+memory is reasonable in a trusted local coding environment but cannot be copied\\n+as llame's multi-tenant authorization model. In llame, any persistent agent\\n+memory must remain visible, principal-owned, permissioned, auditable, portable,\\n+and subject to the same revision and information-flow rules as other knowledge.\\n@@\\n ### O-05 — Agent model\\n \\n-Are experts reusable profiles, delegated Runs, long-lived service identities,\\n-or all three? Which state is user-owned, organization-owned, or agent-specific?\\n+Claude Code shows that “profile,” “Run,” and “memory” are not competing agent\\n+types; they are separable layers [49, 50].\\n+\\n+**Working recommendation — not yet a decision**\\n+\\n+- An **Agent Profile** is a versioned declarative object: name, routing\\n+  description, prompt, model defaults, Skills, allowed tools/MCP servers,\\n+  permission ceiling, and optional memory binding.\\n+- Invoking a profile creates an ordinary isolated **Run** under the caller's\\n+  effective authority. The main assistant may delegate to it, or the user may\\n+  invoke it directly.\\n+- Optional **Agent Memory** is an agent-scoped Knowledge Space or view governed\\n+  by a person, Project, group, or organization. The agent may maintain it through\\n+  the normal knowledge-revision path; it is never an opaque private store or an\\n+  independent grant of authority.\\n+- A long-lived service identity is reserved for installed Apps and workflows\\n+  that must react without a user actively present. Merely having a specialist\\n+  prompt or persistent memory does not create one.\\n+\\n+Still open: whether to accept this hybrid, which memory scopes ship, what the\\n+default is, and how profile inheritance or overrides work.\\n@@\\n | Low-level local runtimes do not supply a complete multi-tenant sandbox service                                                         | Docker, gVisor, and Firecracker docs [44, 45, 46, 47, 48]; evidence 72613df217101340,