          "input": "const patch = \"*** Begin Patch\\n*** Add File: /home/leon0399/Projects/llame/docs/superpowers/plans/2026-07-15-runnable-agent-github-issues.md\\n+# Runnable Agent GitHub Issue Filing Plan\\n+\\n+> **For agentic workers:** This is a backlog-filing plan, not an implementation plan. Do not implement these tasks from this document. File or rewrite the issues only after Leo approves the scopes and ordering below.\\n+\\n+**Goal:** Convert the approved remote-MCP-first runnable-agent slices into a small set of concrete, reviewable GitHub issues with explicit dependencies and no speculative platform work.\\n+\\n+**Architecture:** Reuse the existing MCP, knowledge, and episodic issue surfaces where their history is cheap to rewrite. Split remote MCP into substrate, runtime, and browser-acceptance tasks because they have different code/review boundaries; keep each knowledge capability as one vertical safety boundary. Encode hard blockers with GitHub issue dependencies and use cross-links—not fake blockers—for adjacent reliability and future-platform work.\\n+\\n+**Tech stack:** GitHub Issues, GitHub milestones and dependency relationships, NestJS/TypeScript, AI SDK v6, MCP Streamable HTTP, PostgreSQL/pg-boss, Git CLI, Playwright.\\n+\\n+- **Date:** 2026-07-15\\n+- **Status:** Draft filing plan; no GitHub mutations performed\\n+- **Version:** v0.1\\n+- **Confidence:** High on live issue state and boundaries; moderate on final titles/labels until filing\\n+\\n+---\\n+\\n+## Executive decision\\n+\\n+Do not create a new umbrella issue and do not turn every service or safety property into its own ticket.\\n+\\n+The executable backlog is **seven required tasks plus one optional task**:\\n+\\n+1. tool-catalog substrate;\\n+2. MCP runtime;\\n+3. MCP browser acceptance;\\n+4. episodic-recall MVP, by narrowing existing #198;\\n+5. read-only personal Markdown/Git vault;\\n+6. recoverable agent-authored knowledge writes;\\n+7. combined compounding-loop release gate;\\n+8. optional non-blocking child Chat/Run, filed but unscheduled until the core gate passes.\\n+\\n+This is the minimum defensible split:\\n+\\n+- One issue for all MCP work would mix a cross-cutting tool contract refactor, network lifecycle, and Playwright infrastructure into an unreviewable PR.\\n+- Splitting filesystem safety, Git CAS, effect dedupe, subprocess cancellation, and `knowledge_write` would create individually unshippable tickets around one correctness boundary.\\n+- The final combined gate is separate because it should mostly reuse already-shipped capabilities; if it needs product architecture, an earlier issue was incomplete.\\n+\\n+## Live backlog evidence\\n+\\n+Snapshot verified through GitHub on 2026-07-15:\\n+\\n+- #39 and #40 each claim that sub-issues are tracked, but each has **zero** sub-issues and no comments. Each is the sole issue in its current milestone.\\n+- #194 has a valid hierarchy (#195–#198), but still marks shipped #195 unchecked and describes a stale pre-#195 baseline.\\n+- #195 is closed by PR #202 and its indexed FTS/trigram projection is on `master`.\\n+- #196 and #197 remain coherent future embedding/hybrid-retrieval tasks.\\n+- #172 duplicates the combined scope now specified more precisely by #196 and #197.\\n+- #186 describes the indexed lexical search already shipped by #195/#202.\\n+- #179 remains a real intermittent refresh/resume defect: it reproduced on default-branch CI run 29278884222, while later browser jobs passed. It is reliability debt, not a production-code prerequisite for MCP.\\n+- #203 is a valid future readiness aggregator. The first MCP runtime should emit reusable diagnostics but must not absorb `/readyz`.\\n+- Draft PR #146 changes 34 files with roughly 4.8k additions around a Postgres `memories` table, auto-injection, policy gating, settings UI, and obsolete tool paths. It conflicts with Markdown-canonical knowledge.\\n+- Searches for open issues matching MCP, Markdown knowledge, Obsidian, subagent